Yes. Right now your `Build` step is building the whole solution because it uses:

```yaml
solution: '${{ parameters.solution }}'
```

If you want to build only one project, add a separate parameter for the build project and use that in the `Build` step.

## Change the template

Add a new parameter:

```yaml
- name: buildProject
  type: string
  default: ''
```

Then change the `Build` step to use the project when provided, otherwise fall back to the solution.

Use this:

```yaml
- task: VSBuild@1
  displayName: 'Build'
  inputs:
    solution: ${{ if ne(parameters.buildProject, '') }}:
                '${{ parameters.buildProject }}'
              ${{ else }}:
                '${{ parameters.solution }}'
    vsVersion: '${{ parameters.vsVersion }}'
    platform: '${{ parameters.buildPlatform }}'
    configuration: '${{ parameters.buildConfiguration }}'
    clean: true
    msbuildArgs: >
      /p:SkipInvalidConfigurations=true
      /p:VisualStudioVersion=${{ parameters.vsVersion }}
```

But Azure template expressions inside one property like that can be awkward. The cleaner version is to create two conditional tasks.

## Better version

Replace your current `Build` task with these two tasks:

```yaml
  - task: VSBuild@1
    displayName: 'Build Solution'
    condition: and(succeeded(), eq('${{ parameters.buildProject }}', ''))
    inputs:
      solution: '${{ parameters.solution }}'
      vsVersion: '${{ parameters.vsVersion }}'
      platform: '${{ parameters.buildPlatform }}'
      configuration: '${{ parameters.buildConfiguration }}'
      clean: true
      msbuildArgs: >
        /p:SkipInvalidConfigurations=true
        /p:VisualStudioVersion=${{ parameters.vsVersion }}

  - task: VSBuild@1
    displayName: 'Build Project'
    condition: and(succeeded(), ne('${{ parameters.buildProject }}', ''))
    inputs:
      solution: '${{ parameters.buildProject }}'
      vsVersion: '${{ parameters.vsVersion }}'
      platform: '${{ parameters.buildPlatform }}'
      configuration: '${{ parameters.buildConfiguration }}'
      clean: true
      msbuildArgs: >
        /p:SkipInvalidConfigurations=true
        /p:VisualStudioVersion=${{ parameters.vsVersion }}
```

## Full template change

Add this near your parameters:

```yaml
- name: buildProject
  type: string
  default: ''
```

Then keep:

* `solution` for restore if you still want to restore the whole solution
* `buildProject` for building only one `.csproj`
* `publishProject` for packaging that same project

## Example usage

For MVC:

```yaml
- template: pipelines/build-dotnet-framework-webapi.yml@templates
  parameters:
    jobName: Build_MVC
    jobDisplayName: 'Build MVC'
    buildPool: 'Build Pool'
    buildAgentName: 'UAT-ALTERNA-DK1'
    vsVersion: '17.0'
    buildConfiguration: 'Release'
    solution: 'CardManagement/CardManagement.sln'
    buildProject: 'CardManagement/SGBL.CardManagement/SGBL.CardManagement.csproj'
    nugetConfigPath: 'nuget.config'
    runTests: false
    testAssemblies: ''
    publishProject: 'CardManagement/SGBL.CardManagement/SGBL.CardManagement.csproj'
    zipName: 'AlternaCardManagementMVC.zip'
    packageLocation: '$(Build.ArtifactStagingDirectory)\AlternaCardManagement-package-mvc'
```

For API:

```yaml
- template: pipelines/build-dotnet-framework-webapi.yml@templates
  parameters:
    jobName: Build_API
    jobDisplayName: 'Build Web API'
    buildPool: 'Build Pool'
    buildAgentName: 'UAT-ALTERNA-DK1'
    vsVersion: '17.0'
    buildConfiguration: 'Release'
    solution: 'CardManagement/CardManagement.sln'
    buildProject: 'CardManagement/SGBL.CardManagement.Host/SGBL.CardManagement.Host.csproj'
    nugetConfigPath: 'nuget.config'
    runTests: false
    testAssemblies: ''
    publishProject: 'CardManagement/SGBL.CardManagement.Host/SGBL.CardManagement.Host.csproj'
    zipName: 'AlternaCardManagementAPI.zip'
    packageLocation: '$(Build.ArtifactStagingDirectory)\AlternaCardManagement-package-api'
```

## One important note

If you only build the project instead of the whole solution, project references should still build as dependencies, but solution-level behavior will no longer apply. That is usually fine if your `.csproj` is set up correctly.

A clean final version is:

* `solution` → used for restore
* `buildProject` → used for build
* `publishProject` → used for package

